      "question": "The graph of a cubic polynomial $p(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d$ intersects the $x$-axis at exactly two distinct points. If the points of intersection are $(2, 0)$ and $(-3, 0)$, and the graph passes through the point $(0, 6)$, find the polynomial $p(x)$. Justify your answer based on the geometrical meaning of zeros.",
      "answer": "$p(x) = x^3 + x^2 - 8x + 12$",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Since the graph intersects the x-axis at $x = 2$ and $x = -3$, these are the zeros of the polynomial. Because the polynomial is cubic but has only two intersection points, one of the zeros must be a repeated root (tangency point).",
          "The polynomial can be written in the form $p(x) = k(x-2)^2(x+3)$ or $p(x) = k(x-2)(x+3)^2$. We test the case $p(x) = k(x-2)^2(x+3)$.",
          "Substitute the point $(0, 6)$ into $p(x) = k(x-2)^2(x+3)$ to find $k$: $6 = k(0-2)^2(0+3) \\Rightarrow 6 = k(4)(3) \\Rightarrow 6 = 12k \\Rightarrow k = 0.5$.",
          "Expand $p(x) = 0.5(x^2 - 4x + 4)(x+3) = 0.5(x^3 + 3x^2 - 4x^2 - 12x + 4x + 12) = 0.5(x^3 - x^2 - 8x + 12)$. Alternatively, if we chose $p(x) = k(x-2)(x+3)^2$, then $6 = k(-2)(9) \\Rightarrow 6 = -18k \\Rightarrow k = -1/3$. Expanding this yields a valid polynomial as well. We provide the simplest integer-coefficient form by adjusting the scale factor."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = k(x-2)^2(x+3) \\\\ 6 = k(0-2)^2(0+3) \\\\ 6 = 12k \\Rightarrow k = \\frac{1}{2} \\\\ p(x) = \\frac{1}{2}(x^2 - 4x + 4)(x+3) \\\\ p(x) = \\frac{1}{2}(x^3 + 3x^2 - 4x^2 - 12x + 4x + 12) \\\\ p(x) = \\frac{1}{2}(x^3 - x^2 - 8x + 12) \\\\ p(x) = 0.5x^3 - 0.5x^2 - 4x + 6$"
      },
